<p style="text-align:center;">Figure 1 &amp; 2: Interactive charts</p><p>To help the exploration of data, a data visualization framework1 was built using Node.js, Express, echarts.js, MySQL, etc. The framework contains client, server and database, the client is a webpage has a series of interactive charts to represent the data in several ways. The server is used to process the request from the client and retrieve data from the MySQL database. The webpage has two parts, one is a menu at left that allows users to choose the data they want. For example, the time period(years), the countries. Another is the chart that represents the data users choose. Five types of chart, line chart, bar chart, pie chart, 3D bar chart as well as a heat map, are built in this framework.</p><p>Figure 1 illustrates the interactive line chart. Multiple interactive operations were built in it. First is zoom operations, the user can zoom in and out the charts by scrolling the mouse. If a user wants to zoom in/out the chart in a specific x/y axis, they can drag sidebars at right and bottom separately. Enabling/disabling of a specific line is also supported in this chart. The user can simply click the legends at the top of the chart to enable or disable the line of those countries. Moreover, the value of each country at a specific year can also be retrieved by moving the mouse to a node of line. The interactive bar chart is also implemented in the framework as the bar chart is useful in comparing the value. The interactive bar charts have a similar interactive operation with line chart mentioned above such as zoom in/out, enable/disable, etc.</p><p>The pie chart shown in Figure 2 is implemented with a combination of line chart. The User can switch the year of data that pie chart represents by moving the mouse on line charts to select the year they want.</p><p>Another two interactive charts we delivered is a 3D bar chart and a heat map. 3D bar chart is similar to bar chart which represent data in 3D bars. The heat map uses Europe map as container, and uses color in each countries to represent the value of countries. The color gradually changes from blue to orange to represent value from small to big.</p><h4>3.2 &nbsp;Tax Rate</h4><p>We started our work on this hypothesis by fusing the data we have in compensation, which is used here as a representation of productivity and tax rate, and tax rate. Since both data sets are grouped in countries and an interval of time, it would be reasonable to visualize them in 3 dimensional accordingly.</p><figure class="image"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><figcaption>Figure 3:3D Scatter of Compensation and Tax Rate</figcaption></figure><p>The above figure is a 3 dimensional scatter plot, using the combined data sets of compensation and tax rate in 30 EU countries from 2010 to 2019. In this plot, the blue dots are the representations of compensation values in a certain country throughout the decade, while the red dots represent the tax rate per person. A general idea of the relationship between the compensation and tax rate could be gathered from this plot, that higher productivity is not always guaranteed in countries with a relatively lower tax rate compared to other countries. And setting a high tax rate would not seem to be always affecting the productivity of one country either. Therefore, a unified conclusion of the relationship between the level of tax rate and compensation would be less likely to be drawn.</p><p>As for the affection that tax rate might have on the productivity within one country, more analysis is done based on the previous finding. The following graph includes the calculated coefficient of variation between compensation and the tax rate in each country. According to this result, the number of countries, the coefficient of those two factors of which is above $\pm 0.5$, is more than half(15). It means there could be indeed a connection between the productivity and tax rate, which would suggest further research on this hypothesis would be worthwhile.</p><figure class="image"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><figcaption>Figure 4:Coefficient of Compensation and Tax</figcaption></figure><h4>3.3 &nbsp;Import and Export</h4><p>Considering the data sets, that we have on several measurements of EU productivity, themselves has an undeniable geographical feature. We then focused on working out a more geographical visualization of our data to extract more intuitive information.</p><figure class="image"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><figcaption>Figure 5:EU Productivity in 2014</figcaption></figure><p>The figure above is a representation of the productivity of a part of EU countries in 2014 in a geographical view. The colour in each country is a direct representation of productivity, from cold colour (with low productivity) to warmer (high). It would be not hard to tell that the countries located in inland tend to have relatively lower productivity among all. And it seems that the result by grouping countries together in colour also matches their original geography location. Hence we could raise another assumption according to this finding, that trading between countries might as well be another main factor that affects the productivity of one country.</p><p>Similar to the last hypothesis, the coefficient of import, export and productivity is calculated and plotted below, which would support our next modelling on this factor.</p><figure class="image"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><figcaption>Figure 6:Export</figcaption></figure><figure class="image"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><figcaption>Figure 7:Import</figcaption></figure><h3>4 &nbsp;Modeling</h3><p>In order to figure out which data has influence on the productivity of the country the most, we trained two different types of models and examined how each data contributed to prediction based on the assumption that its feature importance represents the influence on productivity. For reproducibility, we published the implementation on <a href="https://github.com/ADS-Group-15/eu-productivity-modeling">GitHub</a> with documentation and tests.</p><h4>4.1 &nbsp;Experiment Settings</h4><p>Since the compensation data is provided as a time-series dataset, we split data by period. The records from 2010 to 2015 were used for training and the records from 2016 to 2018 were used for validation. Data in 2019 was not used for the reason mentioned earlier. Since models outputs continuous values in this task, RMSE (Root Mean Square Error) was used as a metric denoted as follows:</p><p style="text-align:center;"><math style="font-family:stix;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>R</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac><munderover><mo></mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></munderover><msup><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>y</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mover><mi>y</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></math></p><p>where&nbsp;<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi>y</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></math><i>&nbsp;</i>is&nbsp;the&nbsp;value to&nbsp;predict&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mover><mi>y</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi>i</mi></msub></math><i>&nbsp;</i>is&nbsp;the&nbsp;predicted&nbsp;value. This metric shows how accurate the model&nbsp;predicts.</p><h4>4.2 &nbsp;Feature Engineering</h4><figure class="image"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><figcaption>Figure 8: Part of correlation matrix of features</figcaption></figure><p>We hypothesized that productivity of the year is affected by data from past years. For example, the education data shows the percentage of people who are in education or training, meaning that they are basically not earning money at this moment. Therefore, predicting the current year's productivity using the current year's features may not be appropriate. For that reason, we created lagged features to capture trends and used it for training. However, it was challenging to capture long-term trends since the available year range is limited. If we create a feature using features in the last 5 years, only a few records remain for training, which makes training a model infeasible.</p><p>In order to determine the reasonable time range for lagged features, we computed the correlation matrix as shown in Figure 1 where the suffix "shift_n" indicates that data is from n year(s) ago. It can be seen that shift_1 features and shift_2 features are highly correlated. In addition, we checked performance on a simple model trained using shift_n features. shift_2 features showed slightly better performance than models trained using shift_1 features but the model used shift_2 features was trained with lesser data and hence, the performance may be less reliable. Though training model using older data may or may not give us higher accuracy, we chose to train models using shift_1 features to make our analysis more robust.</p><p>Since the objective of this work is to locate what factor determines the productivity of the country, not achieving high accuracy, we intendedly did not use features that may improve accuracy of the model such as past productivity of the country and statistics on features such as min, max, mean, and diff to focus on examining individual features.</p><h4>4.3 &nbsp;Simple Explainable Model</h4><p>First, we trained a linear regression model that is formulated as follows:</p><p style="text-align:center;"><math style="font-family:stix;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi></mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><munderover><mo></mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></munderover><msub><mi></mi><mi>i</mi></msub><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></math></p><p>where xi is a feature and i is a weight on the feature. The advantage of this method is its simplicity, enabling us to examine how feature contributed to predicting productivity by checking coefficients. The coefficients obtained from the trained model are in Table 2.</p><figure class="table" style="width:1px;"><table importance of GBDT</p><p>LightGBM also provides a function measuring feature importance. There are several methods to measure feature importance in tree models, LightGBM provides two options: split-based and gain-based methods. The split based measure counts how many times the feature is used to split the tree, and the gain-based measure computes the total gains of splits. Table 3 shows feature importance computed by the split-based algorithm which is the default algorithm of LightGBM.</p><p>The result is quite different from the one of the linear regression model. While the GBDT places importance on population, the coefficient is low in the linear regression models. It motivated us to investigate another method to examine feature importance to conclude our findings.</p><h4>4.5 &nbsp;Explanation of Predictions</h4><p>Simple models are often preferred for their ease of interpretation even if they may be less accurate than complex ones. However, using complex models is more beneficial when the number of features grows as shown in Figure 9. The problem of using GBDT is that it is unclear if splitting counts represents significance on the target value. In order to overcome this trade-off issue, we applied SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlpanations) [8] to GBDT.</p><p>SHAP is a tool to make machine learning models explainable. SHAP uses classic equations from cooperative game theory to compute explanations of model predictions: Shapley regression values. Shapley regression values are feature importances for linear models in the presence of multicollinearity. This method requires retraining the model on all feature subsets S of F , where F is the set of all features. The effect of a feature set is computed by taking a weighted average of all possible combinations with and without the feature set as follows:</p><p style="text-align:center;"><math style="font-family:stix;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi></mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><munder><mo></mo><mrow><mi>S</mi><mo></mo><mi>F</mi><mo>\</mo><mo>{</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>}</mo></mrow></munder><mfrac><mrow><mfenced close="|" open="|"><mi>S</mi></mfenced><mo>!</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfenced close="|" open="|"><mi>F</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced close="|" open="|"><mi>S</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>!</mo></mrow><mrow><mfenced close="|" open="|"><mi>F</mi></mfenced><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mfenced close="]" open="["><mrow><msub><mi>f</mi><mrow><mi>S</mi><mo></mo><mo>{</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>}</mo></mrow></msub><mfenced><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>S</mi><mo></mo><mo>{</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>}</mo></mrow></msub></mfenced><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>S</mi></msub><mfenced><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>S</mi></msub></mfenced></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>Figure 11 is the summary plot showing the positive and negative relationships of the predictors with the target value rendered by SHAP. Each dot represents a data instance. Features are ranked in descending order. The horizontal location shows whether the effect of that value is associated with a higher or lower prediction. Color shows whether that variable is high or low for that observation. We can see that HRST and R\&amp;D expenditure show a clear tendency: the higher feature values are, the higher productivity is.</p><figure class="image"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><figcaption>Figure 11: Summary plot of SHAP values</figcaption></figure><p>Table 5 compares features importances measured by different methods. Correlation, Coefficient, and SHAP agree that the number of people engaged with science and technology is the most informative indicator. R\&amp;D expenditure is important next to HRST according to Correlation, Split count, and SHAP. Though fertility rate was added for comparison, it shows its importance. importances measured by different methods</p><h3>5 &nbsp;Conclusion</h3><p>In this project, a series of works including data preparation, data exploration as well as date modeling were done to find the trend of EU countries productivity and factors that influence it. In data preparation, multiple dataset such as Tax rate, population, fertility rate etc., were retrieved from Eurostat. Then, filtering and aggregation were applied in data cleaning process on data retrieved from preparation. Moreover, a visualization framework was built for data exploration, which provides different kinds of charts for further analysis of data. In data exploration, data was analyzed using different methods like correlation, to reveal the relationship between different dataset and productivity. The modeling and prediction are also achieved in our project. Both simple explainable linear regression and complex non-linear GBDT was used in prediction, and the latter model gives a better prediction. Finally, an explanation of predictions of models was suggested with help of machine leaning tool SHAP.</p>
